      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i keep getting this \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error on my ec2 instances in us-east-1. it only happens intermittently and usually during peak traffic. i checked the security groups and everything looks theoretically fine but the logs are pretty messy. can you help me figure out what else might be causing this?\n\nhere is a snippet from cloudwatch:\n2023-10-27T14:22:01Z iid: 4922 error: connection reset by peer (errno 104)\n2023-10-27T14:22:05Z iid: 4925 error: connection reset by peer (errno 104)",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Connection reset by peer errors, especially when they happen during peak traffic, can be tricky. This is often a sign that something on the other end—the peer—is abruptly closing the connection, and it's not a clean shutdown. You should check the network configuration, but look deeper into the application layer or the underlying infrastructure.\n\nSince you mentioned security groups look fine, you might need to look at things like:\n\n1.  **Load Balancer/Proxy Timeouts:** If you have an ELB or another proxy in front of your EC2 instances, it might be timing out the connection before your application finishes, causing the peer (the load balancer) to reset it.\n2.  **Resource Exhaustion:** During peak traffic, are your instances hitting CPU, memory, or network I/O limits? If an instance is overloaded, it might drop connections because it can't process them fast enough.\n3.  **Application Bugs:** Sometimes, a poorly written piece of code on the instance decides to just drop the socket instead of sending a proper error response.\n\nI suggest diving into the system logs on the EC2 instances themselves, not just CloudWatch, to see what the application is doing right before the",
      "source": "target",
