      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i looked at the resource usage and cpu/mem looks okay-ish, maybe a little spike but nothing crazy. could it be something with the network path itself or like some kind of packet loss? the \"randomness\" of it is what's driving me nuts. it's like it just randomly decides to kill the connection for no reason most of the time.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Packet loss or network path instability is a very common culprit when you see intermittent connection resets, especially under load. It's like a poorly managed tunnel where some of the packets just get lost in the chaos, and the connection breaks.\n\nYou need to look beyond the instance itself and examine the path between your EC2 instances and whatever is initiating the connection. This could involve checking VPC flow logs for unusual traffic patterns or looking at the health of the underlying network infrastructure in `us-east-1`.\n\nIf you suspect packet loss, you might want to run continuous network diagnostics or perhaps use tools to measure latency and packet loss between the affected endpoints. Sometimes, it's just a noisy neighbor in the network fabric, or maybe a routing issue that only manifests when the network is saturated.",
      "source": "target",
